NEW BUSINESS

3. Urgent Action to Save Car Free Days 2026

...

FINAL MOTION AS APPROVED

WHEREAS
1. Free and accessible public events play an important role in building community connection and civic pride, especially at a time when many residents are facing cost-of-living pressures and fewer opportunities to enjoy shared cultural experiences without financial barriers;
2. For more than 15 years, Car Free Days have been among Vancouver's largest and most recognizable public events, attracting substantial local participation and visitors, and contributing to the city's cultural life, tourism, and economic activity (Car Free Vancouver Society);
3. The Car Free Days have historically attracted tens of thousands attendees annually, including a significant proportion of out-of-City of Vancouver visitors, and generated measurable community and economic benefits for the city (Destination Vancouver, 2025);
4. The Car Free Days mobilize hundreds of volunteers, strengthen community bonds and neighbourhood cohesion; and provide a platform for local artists, artisans and businesses to showcase their work (Vancouver Sun, 2026);
5. On March 2, 2026, the Vancouver Car Free Day Society announced the cancellation of Car Free Days for summer 2026 after rising production and operating costs, combined with insufficient City funding or other support, made the multi-day event financially unsustainable;
6. Through the FestShare program, the City of Vancouver committed to providing a fee reduction of up to $75,000 to partially offset municipal service costs for the event, including policing, fire and emergency coordination, engineering, traffic operations, sanitation, waste management, park access, and post-event cleanup; notwithstanding such fee reduction, event organizers remain liable for a substantial balance of municipal service fees at the conclusion of the festival. (Vancouver Sun, 2026);
7. The City's Arts, Culture and Community Services department offers a range of programs, awards and services to support cultural projects but has been subject to a 12% budget reduction for 2026;
8. Following the cancellation announcement, Vancouver residents publicly expressed disappointment that a $30,000 funding gap led to the cancellation of the Car Free Days;
9. Bridging this $30,000 funding gap reaffirms the City's commitment to vibrant public events and to ensuring Vancouverites have access to free and affordable events such as Car Free Days; and
10. Without the Car Free Day series, there is a noticeable gap in Vancouver's summer events calendar, particularly in the period following FIFA 2026, when the city is expected to continue welcoming elevated numbers of visitors and international attention.
THEREFORE BE IT RESOLVED

A. THAT Council approve the allocation of a one-time grant of up to $30,000 from appropriate City reserves, contingency funds, or other available sources to support the delivery of the 2026 Car Free Days series.

B. THAT the funding of $30,000 is conditional upon the event organizers providing the City with a financial and event delivery plan satisfactory to staff, demonstrating how the requested funding will address the identified shortfall and enable the events to proceed, specifically the Commercial Drive Car Free Day event on September 5, 2026, and the Main Street Car Free Day event on September 13, 2026.

C. THAT staff report back to Council no later than March 31, 2026, with:

i) details of funding source identification; and
ii) an event delivery plan prior to distributing funds to the Car Free Day society on or before April 15, 2026, in accordance with City's financial policies and grant administration practices.

D. THAT any cash funding associated with the motion entitled "Urgent Action to Save Car Free Days 2026", is a grant and that Council delegate its authority to execute any grant agreement for the associated amount that includes terms and conditions that are consistent with the intentions of the above-noted motion, that satisfy the City's Director of Legal Services, and that disburse the grant described in the same motion to the City Manager (or their designate).

E. THAT no legal rights or obligations will arise or be created by Council's adoption of A to D above unless and until all legal documentation has been executed and delivered by the respective parties).

